  "shortBio": "Cogpups of Alloy Ruins, titled “Scrapgarden Tinker,” are protective alloy-touched Riftlings—four-footed and sure on uneven ground. In the wild they stay protective, four-footed and sure on uneven ground. Favorites include Alloy Moss. Their tempered frame talent shows first as caretaking, not combat.",
  "standardBio": "Cogpup, titled among keepers as “Gearheart Protector,” carries inventive purpose in every movement. Native to Alloy Ruins, the species mends through copper bloom and oil-sweet moss, leaving traces that other Riftlings can follow like soft maps. Wild groups form loose bonds rather than rigid packs; a protective individual may become the emotional center of a small hearthline. They eat Alloy Moss eagerly and dislike food that smells of neglect or spoilage. Ancient keepers carved Cogpup silhouettes into travel stones, believing the species guided the lost. Modern hatcheries record them as reliable companions; their social intelligence tuned to group moods makes training feel like conversation. Their signature ability, Cogpup's Gear Bite, reflects a life shaped by Alloy Ruins more than by arena ambition. Many assume Cogpups are aggressive because of their alloy affinity; most are cautious first. Young Cogpups practice Cogpup's Gear Bite as play long before they understand battle. Adults teach by demonstration: where to rest, what to avoid, how to share warmth or shade.",
  "fullLore": "Cogpups first condensed from residual gearsong along the living edges of Alloy Ruins after early Rift fractures cooled into weather. Their eggs appear where copper bloom and oil-sweet moss gathers into stillness—never in the loudest danger, always in the pocket of calm beside it. Early surveyors mistook them for ambient phenomena until a Cogpup returned a dropped lantern, carefully, as if returning a promise.\n\nIn ancient eras, regional peoples treated Cogpups as omen-bearers rather than pets. Carvings show them walking ahead of caravans, pausing at unstable ground, and curling around children during ashfall or fog. The species was never “tamed” in the old sense; it chose. That choice culture survives in modern Riftkeeper etiquette: you do not yank a Cogpup into a bond. You invite, wait, and keep the invitation honest.\n\nModern history is quieter and more practical. Hatcheries map Cogpup care cycles with the same seriousness given to rare lines, because common does not mean shallow. Alloy Ruins still holds wild populations that trade soft greetings with passerby pets. After major Rift events, Cogpups often appear first at recovery centers—not as heroes, but as inventory clerks of comfort, counting who is cold, hungry, or afraid.\n\nNatural behavior is protective at the core and adaptable at the edges. They are four-footed and sure on uneven ground, companion-sized, easy to cradle, and communicate through soft chirps and affinity flickers. Socially, they prefer small trusted circles; strangers are assessed by scent, posture, and whether a keeper’s voice stays kind under stress. Intelligence presents as social intelligence tuned to group moods. They sleep in curled nests and prefer weather that matches their affinity’s comfort band.\n\nEcologically, Cogpups act as seed dispersers of calm within Alloy Ruins. Allies often include Copperfin and Scrapowl; rivalries with Wispdeer and Sprayfin are usually about nesting space or shiny refuse, not blood feuds. Predators are rare—most threats come from collapsing terrain and careless machines rather than jaws.\n\nCulture around them is affectionate and slightly superstitious. An old keeper journal swears a Cogpup refused to leave an injured stranger until dawn warmth returned. Collectors prize unusual cosmetics, yet marketplace notes remind buyers that verified care history matters more than glitter. The common misunderstanding remains: Many assume Cogpups are aggressive because of their alloy affinity; most are cautious first. The hidden truth keepers debate in soft rooms is simpler and stranger: When deeply bonded, a Cogpup shares short dream-images of places it has never physically visited.\n\nFrom egg to evolved form, their life story stays continuous. Eggs look like copper seed-cases veined with alloy light. Hatchlings are clumsy with sincerity; adults become specialists of place; evolved stages sharpen instinct without erasing childhood habits. Battle tendencies favor supportive pulses, and evolution philosophy insists transformation should answer lived experience—not fashion.\n\nFor Riftkeepers, a Cogpup is a living chapter of Alloy Ruins. Feed it Alloy Moss, respect its protective tempo, and it will teach you the region’s quieter grammar: which winds lie, which stones remember, which silences are safe. Personal quests often begin with a shell symbol, a remembered scent, or a dream of a door that only opens when the bond is honest. That is the Cogpup bargain—not destiny sold at rarity price, but a life that continues because you showed up.",
